         <abstract>
            <p>This article is an expansion of G. E. Forsythe's paper "Von Neumann's comparison method for random sampling from the normal and other distributions" [5]. It is shown that Forsythe's method for the normal distribution can be adjusted so that the average number $\bar N$ of uniform deviates required drops to 2.53947 in spite of a shorter program. In a further series of algorithms, $\bar N$ is reduced to values close to 1 at the expense of larger tables. Extensive computational experience is reported which indicates that the new methods compare extremely well with known sampling algorithms for the normal distribution.</p>
          </abstract>
